Then $CE = 3 + x,$ and $BE = 3 - x.$  By the Law of Cosines on triangle $BCE,$
\[\cos \angle BCE = \frac{3^2 + (3 + x)^2 - 6^2}{2 \cdot 3 \cdot (3 + x)} = \frac{x - 1}{2 (x + 3)}.\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABE,$
\begin{align*}
\cos \angle ABE &= \frac{AB^2 + BE^2 - AE^2}{2 \cdot AB \cdot BE} \\
&= \frac{(2r)^2 + (3 - x)^2 - (5 - r)^2}{2 \cdot 2r \cdot (3 - x)} \\
&= \frac{6x - 4r}{4r (3 - x)}.
\end{align*}Since $\angle ACE = \angle ABE,$
\[\cos \angle ABE = \cos \angle BCE.\]Hence,
\[\frac{x - 1}{2 (x + 3)} = \frac{6x - 4r}{4r (3 - x)}.\]Since $r = 5,$ this simplifies to $18x - 25 = 0,$ so $x = \frac{25}{18}.$

